DOMAIN_OVERVIEW:
The demandingness objection is one of the most persistent challenges to consequentialist and utilitarian moral theories. The debate centers on whether morality can reasonably demand that agents give to the point of marginal utility equality, as Singer's famous 1972 argument suggests, or whether there must be principled limits on moral obligation. Three main response strategies have emerged: (1) agent-relative prerogatives that permit agents to give special weight to their own projects and commitments (Scheffler 1982); (2) satisficing approaches that require only "good enough" rather than optimal outcomes (Slote, Pettit); and (3) threshold or cooperative principles that distribute obligations fairly across agents (Murphy 1993, 2000). Recent work has explored institutional responses (Miklos & Tanyi 2020), scalar approaches that dispense with obligation-talk altogether (Norcross 2020), and refined accounts of what counts as "demanding" (McElwee 2017, York 2024).

RELEVANCE_TO_PROJECT:
This domain directly addresses the central tension in utilitarian giving norms: whether income-based pledges (e.g., 10%) represent arbitrary stopping points or defensible thresholds. Murphy's cooperative principle provides a theoretical foundation for percentage-based norms, while satisficing and threshold views explain why agents need not give to the point of marginal utility equality. The demandingness debate reveals how utilitarian theory must accommodate practical constraints while maintaining moral force.

NOTABLE_GAPS:
While the literature extensively debates theoretical foundations for limiting demands, there is surprisingly little work comparing specific mechanisms (income-based vs. asset-based thresholds, percentage bands, time-limited pledges). The connection between demandingness theory and practical charitable giving movements (Giving What We Can, effective altruism) remains underdeveloped, despite Singer's explicit move toward 10% recommendations in later work.

SYNTHESIS_GUIDANCE:
Pay special attention to the evolution of Singer's position from the demanding 1972 principle to the more pragmatic 10% recommendation in later work. Note how Murphy's cooperative principle provides the most direct theoretical justification for percentage-based norms. Consider whether satisficing and threshold approaches are ultimately compatible or represent distinct theoretical commitments.

KEY_POSITIONS:
- Agent-relative prerogatives (Scheffler, Portmore, Lazar): 7 papers - Permits weighting own projects/commitments
- Satisficing consequentialism (Slote, Pettit, Bradley, McKay): 5 papers - Requires only "good enough" outcomes
- Cooperative/threshold principles (Murphy, Cullity, Hurka): 4 papers - Distributes obligations fairly across agents
- Scalar consequentialism (Norcross, McElwee): 2 papers - Dispenses with deontic categories altogether
====================================================================
