  number = {2},
  pages = {167--199},
  doi = {10.1353/ken.2023.a904082},
  note = {
  CORE ARGUMENT: Pearlman argues against Obligation-Oriented Effective Altruism (OOEA) and its demand to give to the most effective causes rather than to people or causes we care about. She defends Mutual Aid as a morally superior alternative that embraces partiality, builds community, and respects local knowledge. Mutual Aid networks involve reciprocal support among community members, usually geographically proximate, sharing material goods and social support based on solidarity rather than cost-effectiveness calculations.

  RELEVANCE: This critique challenges the impartialism underlying both income-based and asset-based utilitarian giving norms. However, it might apply differently to assets versus income: mutual aid frameworks often involve sharing assets (housing, tools, equipment) more than redistributing income, suggesting assets have distinctive roles in solidarity-based giving. The mutual aid model also emphasizes reciprocity and relationship, which may be easier to sustain with asset-sharing than with income redistribution. This suggests that asset-based norms might need to incorporate relational and reciprocal dimensions that income-based norms do not.

  POSITION: Rejecting OOEA's impartial demandingness in favor of partial, community-based mutual aid as a legitimate way to discharge duties to help others.
  },
